# Auth API — middleware, auth tokens, scenarios
#
# This example shows:
#   - Built-in middleware: logger (console output), delay (50-150ms), auth (bearer token)
#   - Auth exclusions: /api/health and /api/login don't need a token
#   - Scenarios: switch between "empty", "crowded", and "down" states
#   - Runtime middleware: admin-only DELETE guard added after server starts
#
# Start the server:  npx tsx examples/auth-api/server.ts
# Watch the server console — the logger middleware prints every request.

### Health check (no auth needed)
# This endpoint is excluded from auth. Always returns { status: "ok" }.
GET http://localhost:3003/api/health

### Try accessing users without a token
# Returns 401 Unauthorized — the auth middleware blocks this.
GET http://localhost:3003/api/users

### Login as admin
# Returns { token: "admin-token-123", role: "admin" }.
# Copy the token for the next requests.
POST http://localhost:3003/api/login
Content-Type: application/json

{ "email": "admin@example.com", "password": "admin" }

### Login as regular user
# Returns { token: "user-token-456", role: "viewer" }.
POST http://localhost:3003/api/login
Content-Type: application/json

{ "email": "user@example.com", "password": "pass" }

### Login with wrong credentials
# Returns 401 — invalid email/password combo.
POST http://localhost:3003/api/login
Content-Type: application/json

{ "email": "hacker@evil.com", "password": "1234" }

### List all users (with admin token)
# Returns 3 users: Alice (admin), Bob (viewer), Charlie (editor).
GET http://localhost:3003/api/users
Authorization: Bearer admin-token-123

### Filter users by role
# Only admins — returns just Alice.
GET http://localhost:3003/api/users?role=admin
Authorization: Bearer admin-token-123

### Who am I? (admin token)
# Returns { name: "Admin", role: "admin" }.
GET http://localhost:3003/api/me
Authorization: Bearer admin-token-123

### Who am I? (user token)
# Returns { name: "Regular User", role: "viewer" }.
GET http://localhost:3003/api/me
Authorization: Bearer user-token-456

### Delete a user as regular user
# Returns 403 Forbidden — the runtime middleware blocks non-admin deletes.
DELETE http://localhost:3003/internal/users/2
Authorization: Bearer user-token-456

### Delete a user as admin
# Returns 204 No Content — Bob (id=2) is removed.
DELETE http://localhost:3003/internal/users/2
Authorization: Bearer admin-token-123

### Verify deletion
# List users again — Bob should be gone.
GET http://localhost:3003/api/users
Authorization: Bearer admin-token-123

### --- SCENARIOS ---

### Switch to "crowded" scenario
# Resets data and adds 3 extra users (Dana, Eve, Frank) on top of the originals.
POST http://localhost:3003/__mockr/scenario
Content-Type: application/json

{ "name": "crowded" }

### List users after "crowded" scenario
# Now there are 6 users instead of 3.
GET http://localhost:3003/api/users
Authorization: Bearer admin-token-123

### Switch to "down" scenario
# The /internal/users endpoint now returns 503 for everything.
POST http://localhost:3003/__mockr/scenario
Content-Type: application/json

{ "name": "down" }

### Try listing users while "down"
# Returns 503 Service temporarily unavailable.
GET http://localhost:3003/internal/users
Authorization: Bearer admin-token-123

### Switch to "empty" scenario
# Clears all user data.
POST http://localhost:3003/__mockr/scenario
Content-Type: application/json

{ "name": "empty" }

### List users after "empty" — should be empty
GET http://localhost:3003/api/users
Authorization: Bearer admin-token-123

### Reset to defaults
# Back to the original 3 users, no scenario active.
POST http://localhost:3003/__mockr/scenario
Content-Type: application/json

{ "name": "" }

### Confirm reset
GET http://localhost:3003/api/users
Authorization: Bearer admin-token-123
